Project Proposal¶

The intent of this assignment is for you to share your chosen data file(s) with your instructor and provide general information on your goals for the EDA project.
Step 1 (2 pts): Give a brief description of the source(s) of your data and include a direct link to your data.

The data is one single csv file: Our complete COVID-19 dataset is a collection of the COVID-19 data maintained by Our World in Data. It is updated daily and includes data on confirmed cases, deaths, hospitalizations, and testing, as well as other variables of potential interest across different countries worldwide.

  • Confirmed cases and deaths: our data comes from the COVID-19 Data Repository by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins University (JHU).

  • Hospitalizations and intensive care unit (ICU) admissions: our data comes from the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) for a select number of European countries; the government of the United Kingdom; the COVID Tracking Project for the United States; the COVID-19 Tracker for Canada.

  • Testing for COVID-19: this data is collected by the Our World in Data team from official reports. The testing dataset is updated around twice a week.

  • Vaccinations against COVID-19: this data is collected by the Our World in Data team from official reports.

  • Other variables: this data is collected from a variety of sources (United Nations, World Bank, Global Burden of Disease, Blavatnik School of Government, etc.). More information is available in our codebook.

The data I am using can be found at: https://github.com/owid/covid-19-data/blob/master/public/data/owid-covid-data.csv

Step 2 (2 pts): Briefly explain why you chose this data.

We chose this data because we are very interested in the worldwide COVID-19 pandanmic. Particularly, we would like to investigate some factors that affect number of new cases and number of new deaths of COVID-19, aiming to figure out some strategies that might mitigate the pandemic.

The dataset includes not only COVID epidemiology data such as confirmed cases of COVID-19, deaths attributed to COVID-19 and real-time estimate of the effective reproduction rate of COVID-19, but also plenty of other public health data involving life expectancy, population density, death rate from cardiovascular disease, hospital beds per 1,000 people, diabetes prevalence etc. It is an abundant resource for us to test different dependency hypothesis.

Step 3 (1 pt): Provide a brief overview of your goals for this project.

From all the data available to us in the dataset we are using, we decided to investigate multiples hypotheses. We seek to determine whether:

  • Life Expectancy in a given region to correlates to COVID Deaths.
  • Population density correlates with new COVID cases
  • New COVID cases correlates with cardiovascular related deaths

We plan to demonstrate our findings using data visualization tools.

Seaborn pairpots¶

  • We used pairplots and correlational heatmaps to observe whether or not there are any correaltions between variable - especially between the relationships of interest.
  • We can find all of our selected variables are skewed. Especially, the total cases, population density, new cases and total deaths are highly skewed. We also see it in the boxplots in last part.
  • Unlike our hypotheses, there appears to be no assoications between variables we are interested in. Namely,
    • There is no pattern between total deaths and life expectancy where it was expected that COVID deaths are negatively correlated to life expectancy.
    • There is also no correlation between new COVID cases and population density where it was expected that higher new COVID cases would appear in coutries with higher population density.
    • There is no pattern between new COVID cases and cardiovascular related deaths where it was expected that new COVID cases are positively correlated with cardiovascular related deaths.
  • Obviously, higher COVID cases are associated with higher COVID deaths. Life expectancy is highly correlated with cardiovascular related deaths.

Correlation results¶

The highest correlation is the correlation between total cases and total deaths (0.96). Other than the correlations between COVID cases/deaths, the most correlated two variables are life expectancy and cardiovascular related deaths (-0.47). It is reasonable that the countries with less life expectancy have higher cardiovascular related death rate because the countries with less life expectancy were expected to have poorer medical resources.

After looking at relationships we are interested in, we can see that:

  • There is a weak positive correlation between life expectancy and total COVID deaths (0.17). One would expect higher life expectancy would be negatively associated with total COVID deaths.
  • There is almost no correlation between population density and new COVID cases (-0.033).
  • There is low negative correlation between new COVID cases and cardiovascular related deaths (-0.15). We would expect new COVID cases are positively correlated with cardiovascular related deaths.

The slopes of the scatterplots tell us that:

  • As life expectancy of a country increases, COVID deaths increase.
  • As population density increases, total cases decrease.
  • As cardiovascular death rate increases, total cases decrease.

However, after considering the R-squared values of linear regression models we can conclude that these relationships are not correlated and the information above is not useful. By loooking at the R-squared values we can conclude:

  • There is nearly no correlation between life expectancy and total COVID deaths as seen by the very low R-squared value of 0.0289. This relationship is the most 'correlated' of our hypotheses, but still should not be considered as a correlation.
  • There is no correlation between population density and new COVID cases which features a 0.00064 R-squared value.
  • There is nearly no negative correlation between new COVID cases and cardiovascular related deaths which has a 0.015 R^squared value.

Here we split up data into categories based on population density:

  • We observe that the three groups have different mean of total cases (group 1: 875760, group2: 327799, group3: 563454). However, the second group have the lowest number of total cases and the first group have largest number of total cases. We cannot observe an obvious linear association there.

  • The three groups have different mean of new cases (group 1: 3790, group2: 2495, group3: 1576). The group with lowest population density have the highest number of new cases. It indicates lower population density is associated with higher number of cases which does not agree with our hypothesis. There can be other factors confounding the relationship.

  • The three groups have different mean of total deaths (group 1: 18226, group2: 8810, group3: 11462). Similarlly, We cannot explain why the second group have lowest number of total deaths. The non-linear trend may come from randomness.

Summary¶

We didn't identify any factors that are correlated with COVID cases/deaths. It turns out we cannot proove the following intial hypotheses based on current evidence:

  1. Life Expectancy in a given region are negatively correlated to COVID Deaths.
  2. Population density are positively correlated with total COVID cases.
  3. New COVID cases are positively correlated with cardiovascular related deaths.

Next steps: 1) Consider other variables that could contribute to COVID cases/deaths (e.g. hospital beds). 2) Consider interation bewteen these variables.
